00:22:20,772 --> 00:22:22,763
I'm just an academic.

241
00:22:22,874 --> 00:22:26,207
-You got any idea how shitty my funding is?
-No.

242
00:22:27,279 --> 00:22:29,679
University of Nebraska
pays their football coach

243
00:22:29,781 --> 00:22:32,773
more money in a year
than my entire science budget.

244
00:22:32,884 --> 00:22:35,512
Nobody's paying attention to this work.

245
00:22:35,620 --> 00:22:37,815
Half my grants don't get approved.

246
00:22:37,923 --> 00:22:42,257
I don't have the money to make my theory
into a useable medicine.

247
00:22:43,395 --> 00:22:45,295
How old are your kids?

248
00:22:46,298 --> 00:22:47,890
Six and eight.

249
00:22:54,406 --> 00:22:58,809
Look, do yourself a favor.
Go home and spend time with your kids.

250
00:23:01,146 --> 00:23:03,910
Enjoy 'em while they're still here.

251
00:23:11,089 --> 00:23:13,216
-How much?
-How much what?

252
00:23:14,092 --> 00:23:17,152
How much money would it take
to prove your theory,

253
00:23:17,262 --> 00:23:20,720
to create your version of the medicine?

254
00:23:21,633 --> 00:23:25,000
I'd need half a million bucks
just to fund the lab work.

255
00:23:25,103 --> 00:23:28,095
-That's why you need me.
-I need you? Why?

256
00:23:28,206 --> 00:23:32,973
Because I'm the founder of
the Pompe Foundation for Children.

257
00:23:35,180 --> 00:23:37,842
I've been working on this disease
for 10 years.

258
00:23:37,949 --> 00:23:40,577
I have never heard of you guys.

259
00:23:40,685 --> 00:23:45,145
That's because we're relatively new.
We're just in the gearing-up phase.

260
00:23:46,057 --> 00:23:49,891
-How soon do you need a grant?
-Now would be good.

261
00:23:49,995 --> 00:23:54,329
Well, not all the money's in place,
but it will be, and soon.

262
00:23:57,135 --> 00:23:59,433
This is a very exciting time.

263
00:24:09,381 --> 00:24:12,282
-Thanks.
-Thank you, sir. Have a good day.

264
00:24:26,198 --> 00:24:27,392
Hey.

265
00:24:31,269 --> 00:24:32,668
You okay?

266
00:24:37,909 --> 00:24:40,901
-Did you get my messages?
-Your messages?

267
00:24:42,547 --> 00:24:44,447
You suddenly walk out of the meeting

268
00:24:44,549 --> 00:24:47,143
and fly to Nebraska
without talking to me about it,

269
00:24:47,252 --> 00:24:49,413
and you think messages make it okay?

270
00:24:49,521 --> 00:24:51,580
-I'm sorry.
-My God, John.

271
00:24:52,190 --> 00:24:54,681
I wanna find a miracle
as much as you do, okay?

272
00:24:54,793 --> 00:24:57,091
But how could you put your job in jeopardy?

273
00:24:57,195 --> 00:24:58,662
-Aileen.
-How exactly

274
00:24:58,763 --> 00:25:02,130
do we pay $40,000 a month in healthcare
if you lose your insurance?

275
00:25:02,234 --> 00:25:03,701
Honey, come on.
Look, I'm not gonna lose my job.

276
00:25:03,802 --> 00:25:04,860
Oh, really?

277
00:25:04,970 --> 00:25:08,599
Pete called here twice last night
to ask if you were okay.

278
00:25:08,707 --> 00:25:10,504
You know, mentally.

279
00:25:17,816 --> 00:25:21,411
I'll just...
I'll call, and I'll smooth that one over.

280
00:25:21,753 --> 00:25:23,277
Yeah, no shit.

281
00:25:28,293 --> 00:25:29,726
I'm sorry.

282
00:25:34,099 --> 00:25:36,897
Something in me just kind of snapped.

283
00:25:37,936 --> 00:25:42,270
That night at the hospital,
when we thought that we were losing her,

284
00:25:47,979 --> 00:25:51,779
I prayed that if it was her time,

285
00:25:54,085 --> 00:25:58,749
she'd go quickly, without so much suffering.

286
00:26:02,427 --> 00:26:06,727
But morning came, and she pulled through.

287
00:26:08,967 --> 00:26:10,457
Her eyes,

288
00:26:12,270 --> 00:26:15,296
so determined, so defiant.

289
00:26:16,541 --> 00:26:18,304
The fight in her.

290
00:26:29,454 --> 00:26:32,252
Was he worth it? This Stonehill guy?

291
00:26:32,357 --> 00:26:36,020
He's really eccentric, but his science
is way ahead of everybody else's.

292
00:26:36,127 --> 00:26:40,257
-He's definitely the one to put our money on.
-lf we had any.

293
00:26:40,365 --> 00:26:42,595
I promised him that we'd raise some,

294
00:26:42,701 --> 00:26:44,896
because he's got this conference up here
next month,

295
00:26:45,003 --> 00:26:47,369
and I said I'd have a check ready for him.

296
00:26:47,472 --> 00:26:48,632
-How much?
-Five hundred.

297
00:26:48,740 --> 00:26:50,799
-That's all?
-Thousand.

298
00:26:52,544 --> 00:26:54,603
Is it $500 or $1,000?

299
00:26:54,879 --> 00:26:57,143
$500,000.

300
00:26:58,216 --> 00:26:59,774
By next month.

301
00:27:05,423 --> 00:27:09,689
-Sweetheart, are you totally insane?
-Apparently.

302
00:27:10,595 --> 00:27:13,325
We're holding our first fundraiser
on the 23rd at the school,

303
00:27:13,431 --> 00:27:15,797
and we would love
if you and Frank could join us.

304
00:27:15,900 --> 00:27:17,595
-Ready for your spelling test?
-I'm gonna nail it.

305
00:27:17,702 --> 00:27:18,760
Okay. Good luck.

306
00:27:18,870 --> 00:27:21,065
My name's John Crowley.
I'm calling from Oregon,

307
00:27:21,172 --> 00:27:25,632
and I got your name from
the Atlanta-area Pompe parents' group.

308
00:27:25,744 --> 00:27:26,768
Yeah.

309
00:27:26,878 --> 00:27:29,073
And I was so sorry
not to see you at the reunion

310
00:27:29,180 --> 00:27:33,310
because you were one of
my most favorite people in high school.

311
00:27:34,185 --> 00:27:37,677
Anyway, John and l
are starting this foundation.

312
00:27:37,789 --> 00:27:39,518
-Hey, Dad? Dad.
-No, you know what I mean.

313
00:27:39,624 --> 00:27:40,682
Just make it right.

314
00:27:40,792 --> 00:27:43,784
-Dad?
-Can't you see I'm on the phone?

315
00:27:43,895 --> 00:27:46,159
-Okay, well, tell me what he told you.
-Dad!

316
00:27:46,264 --> 00:27:48,824
No, I'm gonna have to call you back.
I can't talk. All right, bye.

317
00:27:48,933 --> 00:27:50,833
-Yeah, what is it?
-I sold my RipStik.

318
00:27:50,935 --> 00:27:51,924
Okay.

319
00:27:52,437 --> 00:27:56,100
Is it enough to give to
Megan and Patrick's foundation?

320
00:27:58,777 --> 00:28:01,041
Yeah, it's more than enough.

321
00:28:03,314 --> 00:28:05,214
-Are you John?
-Yes.

322
00:28:05,316 --> 00:28:08,774
-Marcus Temple. We spoke on the phone.
-Right. Absolutely. Good to see you.

323
00:28:08,887 --> 00:28:11,481
-All the way in from Atlanta.
-Yes.

324
00:28:11,589 --> 00:28:16,686
Well, this is for your foundation,
from my relatives, friends and church group.

325
00:28:17,929 --> 00:28:19,396
My goodness.

326
00:28:19,831 --> 00:28:21,628
Thank you very much.

327
00:28:26,805 --> 00:28:28,102
Thanks.

328
00:28:47,425 --> 00:28:52,522
-Hi, Dr. Stonehill. I'm Megan.
-Hi, Megan. I'm Dr. Stonehill.

329
00:28:52,630 --> 00:28:55,724
Yeah, that's why I said, "Hi, Dr. Stonehill."

330
00:28:56,468 --> 00:28:59,995
-Are you coming in or not?
-Yeah, thanks.

331
00:29:02,140 --> 00:29:03,732
Where's Mom and Dad?

332
00:29:03,842 --> 00:29:05,104
They'll be down in a minute.

333
00:29:05,210 --> 00:29:08,771
Patrick's vent alarm is going off,
so they need to fix it.

334
00:29:08,880 --> 00:29:11,678
His alarm goes off even more than mine.

335
00:29:19,891 --> 00:29:23,224
So, what's your deal? You married?

336
00:29:24,462 --> 00:29:26,123
Do you have a wife?

337
00:29:26,631 --> 00:29:28,462
Ex-wives. Two of 'em.

338
00:29:28,566 --> 00:29:32,195
-Yeah? How come?
-'Cause I'm so easy to get along with.

339
00:29:33,071 --> 00:29:36,472
-Any other questions?
-No. Your turn to ask one.

340
00:29:38,977 --> 00:29:40,467
You're probably wondering
what grade I'm in.

341
00:29:40,578 --> 00:29:43,046
-What grade are you in?
-I'm in third.

342
00:29:43,181 --> 00:29:46,878
My hobbies are video games and penguins.
How about you?

343
00:29:47,652 --> 00:29:51,144
-I already graduated.
-No, I mean hobbies.

344
00:29:53,925 --> 00:29:55,051
Mostly I just work.

345
00:29:55,160 --> 00:29:58,459
Little bass fishing
every once in a while, but...

346
00:30:00,832 --> 00:30:02,231
What's your favorite subject?

347
00:30:02,333 --> 00:30:06,667
I'm good at reading, but I like P.E. best,
especially the sprint races.

348
00:30:06,771 --> 00:30:07,999
Sprint races?

349
00:30:08,106 --> 00:30:10,301
-Wanna see?
-Sure.

350
00:30:15,780 --> 00:30:17,179
Come on.

351
00:30:19,851 --> 00:30:22,149
-ls he here yet?
-I don't know.

352
00:30:31,129 --> 00:30:33,063
I'm gonna win!

353
00:30:33,765 --> 00:30:35,665
Come on, slowpoke.

354
00:30:40,038 --> 00:30:41,733
Yeah, I won!

355
00:30:42,640 --> 00:30:44,005
I won.

356
00:30:44,442 --> 00:30:45,841
Oh, yeah.

357
00:30:46,477 --> 00:30:48,707
Told you I'm gonna beat you.

358
00:30:49,747 --> 00:30:51,009
Hi.

359
00:30:52,283 --> 00:30:54,877
Dr. Stonehill has two ex-wives.

360
00:30:54,986 --> 00:30:57,284
-I see that Megan's introduced herself.
-Yeah.

361
00:30:57,388 --> 00:30:59,379
-How are you, Dr. Stonehill?
-I'm okay, thank you.

362
00:30:59,490 --> 00:31:01,424
-This is Aileen, my wife.
-So nice to meet you.

363
00:31:01,559 --> 00:31:03,686
-And John Jr.
-Hello.

364
00:31:03,795 --> 00:31:05,057
-Here's Patrick.
-Hi.

365
00:31:05,163 --> 00:31:07,927
-Hey, Patrick.
-I think we should probably go inside.

366
00:31:08,199 --> 00:31:09,359
Yeah, come on inside.

367
00:31:09,467 --> 00:31:12,368
Megan, we'll see you inside. Come on.

368
00:31:17,842 --> 00:31:20,106
-Night, Patrick.
-Good night.

369
00:31:20,745 --> 00:31:21,973
Night, SpongeBob.

370
00:31:22,080 --> 00:31:25,447
-You gotta say good night to Dr. Stonehill.
-Kiss SpongeBob.

371
00:31:32,323 --> 00:31:34,257
-Good night.
-Good night, son.

372
00:31:35,860 --> 00:31:37,555
Good night, Patrick.

373
00:31:37,662 --> 00:31:40,825
I'm not gonna say it again. It is bedtime now.

374
00:31:41,299 --> 00:31:42,960
It's for him.

375
00:31:45,303 --> 00:31:49,137
-Me?
-For good luck. For bass fishing.

376
00:31:50,174 --> 00:31:51,402
Thank you.

377
00:31:53,945 --> 00:31:55,674
You like it?

378
00:31:55,813 --> 00:32:00,273
Well, sure. A happy-go-lucky little fellow,
lots of personality, huh?

379
00:32:01,219 --> 00:32:04,154
-He's a plastic toy.
-I know.

380
00:32:04,622 --> 00:32:06,089
Here's the father-daughter dance.

381
00:32:06,190 --> 00:32:09,591
You haven't lived until you've seen
Megan do the Wheelchair Watusi.

382
00:32:09,694 --> 00:32:11,184
Here you go.

383
00:32:11,296 --> 00:32:15,198
-Go ahead and eat the cobbler while it's hot.
-Smells great, honey.

384
00:32:16,401 --> 00:32:17,868
This was hilarious.

385
00:32:17,969 --> 00:32:21,632
Bob, we went to this dude ranch.
All right if I call you Bob?

386
00:32:21,739 --> 00:32:26,676
You got a check for a half-million dollars,
hell, you can call me Peggy Sue.

387
00:32:29,647 --> 00:32:31,171
I'll just...

388
00:32:41,793 --> 00:32:43,317
Well, Bob.

389
00:32:43,962 --> 00:32:48,592
This is the first installment
against the promised half a million.

390
00:33:00,011 --> 00:33:02,707
Tell you the truth,
that's more than I expected.

391
00:33:02,814 --> 00:33:05,908
Dr. Stonehill, we promise that...

392
00:33:06,017 --> 00:33:07,814
-Yeah, I know.
-lf... In enough time, then...

393
00:33:07,919 --> 00:33:09,887
I know. I know.

394
00:33:11,489 --> 00:33:14,822
You can learn a lot about a person
on the lnternet these days.

395
00:33:14,926 --> 00:33:18,418
Learn about a working-class kid
from New Jersey,

396
00:33:18,529 --> 00:33:21,498
worked his way through
Harvard Business School,

397
00:33:21,599 --> 00:33:24,067
clawing his way up the ladder
at Bristol-Myers.

398
00:33:24,202 --> 00:33:25,669
But what Google can't tell you

399
00:33:25,770 --> 00:33:28,238
is that this scared, desperate, bullshitting
son of a bitch...

400
00:33:28,339 --> 00:33:30,102
-Wait just a minute...
-Don't interrupt.

401
00:33:30,208 --> 00:33:33,541
Will do and say whatever it takes
to get results.

402
00:33:34,712 --> 00:33:38,148
Which is why you and me are going
into business together, Jersey.

403
00:33:38,249 --> 00:33:39,409
Excuse me?

404
00:33:39,517 --> 00:33:41,781
I'm tired of begging breadcrumbs
from the university

405
00:33:41,886 --> 00:33:44,446
and giving them the patents to my ideas.

406
00:33:44,555 --> 00:33:47,353
They don't value my work. You do,

407
00:33:48,126 --> 00:33:50,788
which is why I'm setting up my own shop.

408
00:33:50,895 --> 00:33:52,260
Figure any dude in a business suit

409
00:33:52,363 --> 00:33:54,490
can help me raise venture capital
and run the company,

410
00:33:54,599 --> 00:33:59,161
but who's gonna be half as motivated as
a dad who's trying to save his own kids?

411
00:33:59,270 --> 00:34:01,101
So, this is...

412
00:34:01,205 --> 00:34:03,673
So this is the shittiest offer
you're ever gonna get.

413
00:34:03,775 --> 00:34:07,768
I can promise you less money, longer hours,
lousy working conditions,

414
00:34:07,879 --> 00:34:11,838
plus, if we raise the money,
you're gonna have to relocate to Nebraska.

415
00:34:16,487 --> 00:34:18,011
And with the right business plan,

416
00:34:18,122 --> 00:34:22,058
I can also promise you
a working enzyme for Pompe disease.

417
00:34:22,827 --> 00:34:26,695
I can't cure your kids, you know that.
They're always gonna be in wheelchairs,

418
00:34:28,066 --> 00:34:30,728
but I think I can save their lives.

419
00:34:35,706 --> 00:34:37,571
Outstanding cobbler.

420
00:34:40,311 --> 00:34:44,975
Okay, okay.
So, we agree we can't uproot the kids.

421
00:34:45,817 --> 00:34:47,944
What if Stonehill fails?

422
00:34:51,489 --> 00:34:55,391
Or what if he succeeds too late
to help Megs and Patrick?

423
00:34:55,493 --> 00:34:57,825
-Then what?
-I know.

424
00:34:58,963 --> 00:35:03,627
If we're gonna lose them young, you want
to spend every minute you can with them.

425
00:35:10,842 --> 00:35:14,539
John, that day that you flew to Nebraska,

426
00:35:14,645 --> 00:35:18,172
when you suddenly just ditched work and...

427
00:35:20,651 --> 00:35:24,143
My God, I thought you'd lost it.
You scared me.

428
00:35:24,889 --> 00:35:27,449
But once we rolled our sleeves up,

429
00:35:27,558 --> 00:35:31,790
and we started fundraising
and meeting other Pompe families,

430
00:35:34,699 --> 00:35:36,667
it made me feel like...

431
00:35:37,101 --> 00:35:39,331
I mean, do we just accept our fate

432
00:35:39,437 --> 00:35:43,032
and do what we're told
by all the well-meaning doctors

433
00:35:44,342 --> 00:35:48,176
and wait for the worst to happen,
or do we fight it?

434
00:35:50,915 --> 00:35:54,681
I think you're making a mistake. I really do.

435
00:35:55,286 --> 00:35:59,382
Even if you were credible as a CEO,
which you are not,

436
00:36:00,758 --> 00:36:05,661
the odds against you are crushing.
Nine out of 10 biotechs crash and burn.

437
00:36:05,763 --> 00:36:09,995
So where does that leave your kids
when their dad is flat broke

438
00:36:10,635 --> 00:36:14,162
with no job and no health insurance?

439
00:36:14,472 --> 00:36:15,530
Now, if you stay at Bristol,

440
00:36:15,640 --> 00:36:19,872
the guys upstairs are ready to put you in
the VP slot at the end of the third quarter

441
00:36:19,977 --> 00:36:22,172
with a 40%% salary bump.

442
00:36:22,980 --> 00:36:24,174
John.

443
00:36:26,050 --> 00:36:28,814
Your family's gonna need that money,
aren't they?

444
00:36:28,920 --> 00:36:31,650
Pete, you're right. This is crazy.

445
00:36:33,024 --> 00:36:34,924
I'm chasing the wind.

446
00:36:36,194 --> 00:36:38,162
But I can't just

447
00:36:40,198 --> 00:36:43,361
sit around and wait for my kids to die.

448
00:36:45,236 --> 00:36:46,828
I can't do it.

449
00:37:09,393 --> 00:37:12,362
You have arrived at your destination.

450
00:37:27,245 --> 00:37:29,440
Come on in. It's open.

451
00:37:30,081 --> 00:37:31,742
-Hey, there, Bob.
-Hey, John.

452
00:37:31,849 --> 00:37:32,873
How are you?

453
00:37:32,984 --> 00:37:35,248
-You have trouble finding me?
-No problem.

454
00:37:35,353 --> 00:37:37,116
-Sit down.
-Thanks.

455
00:37:43,928 --> 00:37:46,829
Ex-wife. She loved cats.

456
00:37:50,635 --> 00:37:53,297
Well, say, what do we...

457
00:37:55,206 --> 00:37:58,903
What are we gonna do?
How about we work up a strategy

458
00:37:59,010 --> 00:38:01,808
for the meeting at Renzler next week?

459
00:38:04,515 --> 00:38:06,949
We don't need to show those guys anything.

460
00:38:07,385 --> 00:38:08,784
The meeting's a formality.

461
00:38:08,886 --> 00:38:11,446
George Renzler and I have known each other
since med school.

462
00:38:11,555 --> 00:38:16,390
He's been telling me for years that
he'd give me the seed money

463
00:38:16,494 --> 00:38:19,930
if I ever decide to make the big move
and set up my own shop.

464
00:38:20,031 --> 00:38:22,591
Well, that's good. That's good,
but, still, all the same, you know,

465
00:38:22,700 --> 00:38:25,260
if we're gonna go in to pitch 'em,
we should have something tangible.

466
00:38:25,369 --> 00:38:29,533
Those guys understand me.
They're real scientists.

467
00:38:30,408 --> 00:38:33,775
They're not like a lot of
these big biotech moneymen.

468
00:38:33,878 --> 00:38:37,746
Okay. All right, tell you what,
how about if we just talk it through,

469
00:38:37,848 --> 00:38:40,612
and then that way we can just sketch up
something rough on paper?

470
00:38:40,718 --> 00:38:44,017
You give it to me,
I'll make up a business plan.

471
00:38:51,062 --> 00:38:55,761
We need to rough out a real strategy.
These guys are venture capitalists.

472
00:38:55,866 --> 00:38:58,027
That rough enough for you?

473
00:38:59,904 --> 00:39:03,135
Bob? Look, Renzler's crucial to us. Without
them onboard, we got zero credibility

474
00:39:03,240 --> 00:39:05,140
-with any of our investors.
-That's why you're here, Jersey!

475
00:39:05,242 --> 00:39:07,506
Whip up some business bullshit
by tomorrow.

476
00:39:07,611 --> 00:39:11,342
-I'm going fishing.
-This is... This is gibberish!

477
00:39:11,449 --> 00:39:13,349
Then you better get busy.

478
00:39:13,451 --> 00:39:14,850
See you.

479
00:39:33,971 --> 00:39:38,601
As you know, the market potential
