00:57:30,346 --> 00:57:32,075
Where you going?

719
00:57:36,186 --> 00:57:40,623
I'm gonna go take a crap,
if that meets with your fiscal approval.

720
00:57:59,843 --> 00:58:03,040
What, they can't drive from the airport
like ordinary people?

721
00:58:03,146 --> 00:58:05,614
Bob, we need to make this happen.

722
00:58:07,617 --> 00:58:09,744
They're gonna ask us some tough questions.

723
00:58:10,186 --> 00:58:14,350
Don't take 'em personally, all right?
All right?

724
00:58:26,069 --> 00:58:29,527
These lab results confirm
what I've been preaching for years,

725
00:58:29,706 --> 00:58:33,472
that phosphorylation is key
to enzyme absorption.

726
00:58:34,344 --> 00:58:36,812
My theory works for Pompe,

727
00:58:36,913 --> 00:58:40,781
and eventually it'll work for
enzyme replacement therapies

728
00:58:40,884 --> 00:58:43,648
for other lysosomal storage disorders.

729
00:58:44,254 --> 00:58:47,382
-ls it too complicated?
-Too complicated?

730
00:58:47,490 --> 00:58:51,517
The number of variables built into
your approach are mind-boggling.

731
00:58:51,628 --> 00:58:54,961
I mean, Jesus, if you get even
one piece wrong in the synthesis,

732
00:58:55,064 --> 00:58:58,124
just one carbohydrate ends up
in the wrong position...

733
00:58:58,234 --> 00:59:01,533
Well, it's gotta be done right,
like anything worth doing.

734
00:59:02,071 --> 00:59:04,835
You've never actually gotten
a drug approved.

735
00:59:04,941 --> 00:59:09,844
Isn't it naive to think you can solve
these kinds of manufacturing challenges?

736
00:59:15,685 --> 00:59:17,812
Bob? Bob?

737
00:59:19,122 --> 00:59:21,818
You're right, I'm a theory guy.

738
00:59:22,792 --> 00:59:24,987
My head is in the clouds.

739
00:59:26,930 --> 00:59:29,057
Which is why we need you.

740
00:59:31,634 --> 00:59:33,932
Unless, of course, your reputation

741
00:59:34,070 --> 00:59:37,904
for solving protein-manufacturing problems
is undeserved.

742
00:59:40,076 --> 00:59:41,441
Nice one.

743
00:59:42,545 --> 00:59:47,380
-I still need to hear about profitability.
-Certainly, certainly.

744
00:59:47,917 --> 00:59:53,287
As you know, this is not
a one-time treatment. It's a lifelong therapy.

745
00:59:53,389 --> 00:59:55,186
And these patients,

746
00:59:55,291 --> 01:00:01,230
they are going to generate revenue
over the span of their lifetime that is...

747
01:00:01,331 --> 01:00:05,461
But even if you make a usable enzyme,
clearly it won't work for all patients.

748
01:00:05,568 --> 01:00:09,060
So, what survival rate do we need
to achieve a robust profit?

749
01:00:09,172 --> 01:00:13,131
What rate of patient death
can be defined as acceptable loss?

750
01:00:14,077 --> 01:00:16,068
Acceptable loss?

751
01:00:21,818 --> 01:00:23,945
I understand the question.

752
01:00:26,656 --> 01:00:32,595
Because the profit margins on this
orphan drug are so incredibly high, the...

753
01:00:33,963 --> 01:00:39,697
Even with a mortality rate of,
say, 25%% over five years still indicates

754
01:00:39,802 --> 01:00:45,763
that there is a highly lucrative
revenue source to be realized.

755
01:01:00,857 --> 01:01:03,087
Gentlemen, we have a deal.

756
01:01:50,707 --> 01:01:53,505
Dr. Robert Stonehill to see Barry Renee.

757
01:01:56,913 --> 01:02:00,212
I have a Dr. Robert Stonehill
to see Dr. Renee.

758
01:02:02,351 --> 01:02:05,343
-Sir, you need to be cleared.
-I'm just gonna use the restroom.

759
01:02:05,455 --> 01:02:08,356
-You need to be cleared to do that, sir.
-Just need to...

760
01:02:08,458 --> 01:02:11,689
-You need a security badge.
-Jesus.

761
01:02:15,431 --> 01:02:18,992
Well, can I have a security badge
so I can go take a pee?

762
01:02:19,202 --> 01:02:20,897
Yes, sir. He will give that to you.

763
01:02:29,278 --> 01:02:31,838
-Hey, Bob.
-Hey, John.

764
01:02:31,948 --> 01:02:34,075
You getting comfortable?

765
01:02:34,951 --> 01:02:36,885
Define "comfortable."

766
01:02:41,290 --> 01:02:43,451
You haven't cashed it yet?

767
01:02:44,427 --> 01:02:46,418
I haven't earned it yet.

768
01:02:47,463 --> 01:02:50,455
I'll cash it when we have a usable enzyme.

769
01:03:08,918 --> 01:03:11,512
Well, it sure is beautiful.

770
01:03:17,527 --> 01:03:19,290
It sure is big.

771
01:03:20,363 --> 01:03:22,160
The kids love it.

772
01:03:29,438 --> 01:03:31,099
Seize the day.

773
01:03:35,578 --> 01:03:36,875
Okay.

774
01:03:47,590 --> 01:03:49,080
I'm stuck on this call.

775
01:03:49,192 --> 01:03:52,355
Just wanted to let you know how thrilled
we are to have you onboard, John.

776
01:03:52,461 --> 01:03:54,088
It's an honor.

777
01:03:54,797 --> 01:03:56,924
-You remember Dr. Kent Webber.
-Of course.

778
01:03:57,033 --> 01:03:58,432
-It's good to see you again.
-Good to see you, too.

779
01:03:58,534 --> 01:04:01,401
I'll let the two of you get into it.

780
01:04:01,504 --> 01:04:04,667
-I'm expecting great things.
-Yes, sir.

781
01:04:08,611 --> 01:04:13,446
I've got some pretty good ideas
about how to help the flow of information

782
01:04:13,549 --> 01:04:15,540
between the four core enzyme groups.

783
01:04:15,651 --> 01:04:19,052
Whoa, John, slow down.
That's not our established procedure.

784
01:04:19,155 --> 01:04:20,247
Pardon me?

785
01:04:20,356 --> 01:04:24,190
The four core teams are essentially
in competition with each other.

786
01:04:24,293 --> 01:04:27,285
It's an entrepreneurial model. It works.

787
01:04:27,396 --> 01:04:32,095
I'm all for competition,
but surely there must be some channel

788
01:04:32,201 --> 01:04:38,868
for allowing sharing scientific insights
that can help develop all four enzymes.

789
01:04:39,242 --> 01:04:43,975
John, in the interest of saving us time,
let me be blunt.

790
01:04:45,248 --> 01:04:47,443
Most of the scientists here don't like the idea

791
01:04:47,550 --> 01:04:51,646
of having a non-scientist
as senior VP of the Pompe program.

792
01:04:53,189 --> 01:04:55,214
Especially one whose objectivity

793
01:04:55,324 --> 01:04:59,055
might be clouded
by having children with the disease.

794
01:05:00,196 --> 01:05:03,393
I'm telling you this
in your own best interests.

795
01:05:03,933 --> 01:05:06,299
Erich wanted to buy Stonehill's ideas,

796
01:05:06,402 --> 01:05:11,032
and he couldn't do that without also
swallowing you as part of the pill.

797
01:05:13,776 --> 01:05:17,872
My advice to you, John,
is to keep your head down.

798
01:05:20,850 --> 01:05:24,342
-Thank you for that wisdom.
-You're very welcome.

799
01:05:28,557 --> 01:05:29,525
All of your lab notebooks must be submitted
to the review committee!

800
01:05:29,525 --> 01:05:31,493
All of your lab notebooks must be submitted
to the review committee!

801
01:05:31,594 --> 01:05:34,085
This is my lab now! Get out!

802
01:05:34,196 --> 01:05:36,426
I'm just trying to explain the protocol!

803
01:05:36,532 --> 01:05:39,501
-You're wasting my time.
-Dr. Stonehill...

804
01:05:40,036 --> 01:05:41,264
Fine.

805
01:05:47,243 --> 01:05:48,540
What do you want?

806
01:05:49,245 --> 01:05:54,273
I just dropped by to say that I think
that we might be missing an opportunity

807
01:05:54,417 --> 01:05:57,250
to open a dialogue
with the other three core teams.

808
01:05:57,386 --> 01:06:00,947
The other core teams? Core teams.

809
01:06:01,090 --> 01:06:02,580
Core bullshit.

810
01:06:03,559 --> 01:06:05,789
I'll come back another time.

811
01:06:09,498 --> 01:06:12,626
The decline in muscle strength
is very troubling, of course,

812
01:06:12,735 --> 01:06:16,068
but it's really, in both kids,

813
01:06:16,172 --> 01:06:20,734
the organ enlargement, the liver,
and especially the heart,

814
01:06:20,843 --> 01:06:23,641
that's the real threat to their lives.

815
01:06:24,480 --> 01:06:27,677
We'll continue to monitor
the rate of cardiac enlargement.

816
01:06:27,783 --> 01:06:30,877
-We'll keep tabs on their other organs...
-How long?

817
01:06:32,521 --> 01:06:35,217
-I don't like to predict.
-Please.

818
01:06:35,324 --> 01:06:38,225
Dr. Waldman, we won't hold you to it.
We just need to know something.

819
01:06:38,327 --> 01:06:39,885
John.

820
01:06:40,196 --> 01:06:43,962
How much more time do we have?
How long?

821
01:06:45,568 --> 01:06:46,967
Well,

822
01:06:50,239 --> 01:06:53,970
if there's another respiratory crisis,
all bets are off,

823
01:06:54,643 --> 01:06:57,441
but otherwise,

824
01:07:00,149 --> 01:07:02,344
Megan, maybe a year.

825
01:07:02,985 --> 01:07:05,351
Patrick, less.

826
01:07:08,991 --> 01:07:10,390
Thank you.

827
01:07:25,274 --> 01:07:26,502
Marcus.

828
01:07:26,609 --> 01:07:27,667
-Get the phone.
-What?

829
01:07:27,777 --> 01:07:29,745
-The phone.
-Who is it?

830
01:07:30,546 --> 01:07:33,379
-Hello?
-Hi. Is that Marcus?

831
01:07:33,516 --> 01:07:36,508
-Yeah, yeah. What time is it?
-Yeah, I'm sorry. It's late.

832
01:07:37,186 --> 01:07:40,383
-It's John Crowley.
-John, what you doin'?

833
01:07:41,724 --> 01:07:42,816
You okay?

834
01:07:44,960 --> 01:07:48,726
Hey, look, I gotta ask you a favor.

835
01:07:49,598 --> 01:07:51,190
-Morning, Gavin.
-Morning, sir.

836
01:07:51,300 --> 01:07:52,892
Is my 1 1:00 with Henessey confirmed?

837
01:07:53,002 --> 01:07:56,836
Yes, and there's the breakfast meeting
down in the cafeteria.

838
01:07:56,939 --> 01:07:58,338
Breakfast meeting?

839
01:07:58,441 --> 01:08:01,001
There was an e-mail that came in
over the weekend.

840
01:08:01,110 --> 01:08:02,907
Everyone on the Pompe project was invited.

841
01:08:03,045 --> 01:08:05,980
-Who called the meeting?
-Mr. Crowley, I believe, sir.

842
01:08:06,082 --> 01:08:07,379
What?

843
01:08:11,253 --> 01:08:16,418
Something that people ask me all the time
is how we have two kids with Pompe.

844
01:08:17,259 --> 01:08:21,355
By the time we realized
that Megan had Pompe,

845
01:08:22,364 --> 01:08:24,457
I was already pregnant with Patrick.

846
01:08:24,567 --> 01:08:27,365
I mean, I can't tell you
how many doctors we saw,

847
01:08:27,470 --> 01:08:29,199
and the message was always the same,

848
01:08:29,305 --> 01:08:32,502
that there is no drug to treat Pompe.

849
01:08:32,608 --> 01:08:36,442
But thanks to you, all of you,
that message is changing.

850
01:08:36,545 --> 01:08:41,005
What you've given us,
and a lot of other families, is hope.

851
01:08:41,117 --> 01:08:42,675
So, thank you.

852
01:08:43,953 --> 01:08:45,784
Good job, Aileen.

853
01:08:48,591 --> 01:08:51,651
Now I'd like to welcome the Temple family,

854
01:08:51,760 --> 01:08:55,787
who've come all the way from Georgia
to be with us here today.

855
01:09:01,604 --> 01:09:03,231
Thanks, John.

856
01:09:06,408 --> 01:09:07,602
Hi.

857
01:09:09,178 --> 01:09:10,770
I'm Marcus.

858
01:09:11,914 --> 01:09:14,075
This is my wife, Wendy.

859
01:09:14,183 --> 01:09:17,084
Our daughter Lauren, our oldest daughter,

860
01:09:17,186 --> 01:09:22,146
Lauren wanted to come today
and say hi to all you guys.

861
01:09:24,193 --> 01:09:25,683
She's a little weak,

862
01:09:25,794 --> 01:09:30,925
but she wanted us
to show you guys her picture

863
01:09:31,433 --> 01:09:34,061
and to send you her love.

864
01:09:34,970 --> 01:09:38,201
And this is our daughter, Megan.

865
01:09:38,307 --> 01:09:41,743
The most beautiful girls are named Megan.

866
01:09:42,845 --> 01:09:46,975
Megan is four months old,
and you can't see it yet,

867
01:09:48,350 --> 01:09:50,341
but she has Pompe, too.

868
01:10:04,300 --> 01:10:05,665
I...

869
01:10:07,703 --> 01:10:11,639
I can't tell you what it means to us

870
01:10:13,342 --> 01:10:17,711
to have all of you working on a medicine
for our children.

871
01:10:20,482 --> 01:10:21,881
Thank you.

872
01:10:28,691 --> 01:10:30,318
Thanks so much.

873
01:10:38,767 --> 01:10:40,894
-Hey, Kent.
-John.

874
01:10:41,003 --> 01:10:43,631
So what did you think of the event?

875
01:10:49,111 --> 01:10:54,515
In medical research, John,
objectivity is key.

876
01:10:56,018 --> 01:10:59,112
If researchers get all emotional,

877
01:10:59,221 --> 01:11:03,817
all desperate to help suffering patients,
they'll cut corners.

878
01:11:03,926 --> 01:11:05,120
It's counterproductive.

879
01:11:05,227 --> 01:11:09,960
Counterproductive is having
four core teams of scientists

880
01:11:10,065 --> 01:11:14,502
working together on the same disease,
but not talking to each other.

881
01:11:15,037 --> 01:11:18,370
Most of these guys have never
even seen a kid with Pompe before.

882
01:11:18,474 --> 01:11:20,237
I don't see how that's relevant.

883
01:11:20,376 --> 01:11:24,608
Did you see Erich?
That's the kind of motivation that we need.

884
01:11:24,713 --> 01:11:29,150
I'm gonna ask him to get the core team
to stop competing, start working together.

885
01:11:29,251 --> 01:11:31,515
Create a leadership team.

886
01:11:33,589 --> 01:11:37,150
Well, if you hope to sell
this leadership team idea,

887
01:11:37,259 --> 01:11:39,454
there's only one way to convince Erich.

888
01:11:39,561 --> 01:11:40,892
And what's that?

889
01:11:40,996 --> 01:11:43,863
Keep your guy, Stonehill, off the team.

890
01:11:44,733 --> 01:11:50,228
In his short tenure here, he's managed to
alienate a remarkable number of colleagues.

891
01:11:50,339 --> 01:11:53,331
You can't put him on a team
that's supposed to build cooperation.

892
01:11:53,442 --> 01:11:57,435
So, decide how badly
you want your leadership team,

893
01:11:59,014 --> 01:12:01,380
then do what you have to do.

894
01:12:13,495 --> 01:12:14,928
That's it.

895
01:12:20,803 --> 01:12:22,771
Dr. Stonehill, please.

896
01:12:23,605 --> 01:12:25,732
Turn it down. Yes.

897
01:12:26,275 --> 01:12:28,106
Yes, the music.

898
01:12:31,380 --> 01:12:33,245
I said down!

899
01:12:34,950 --> 01:12:36,781
This guy's impossible.

900
01:12:36,885 --> 01:12:38,682
I like that song.

901
01:12:45,527 --> 01:12:46,687
Hey.

902
01:12:52,534 --> 01:12:54,297
What's up, John?

903
01:12:54,803 --> 01:12:57,829
-Everything all right at home?
-Yeah.

904
01:13:01,009 --> 01:13:03,807
Have you heard that Erich Loring

905
01:13:03,912 --> 01:13:07,211
has agreed to put together
a leadership team?

906
01:13:08,016 --> 01:13:10,314
Yeah, I heard some rumor about it.
What bullshit.

907
01:13:10,419 --> 01:13:15,721
Now I'm gonna have to spend a couple of
hours a week jawin' with Zymagen guys?

908
01:13:16,759 --> 01:13:17,885
No.

909
01:13:18,193 --> 01:13:22,129
No. No, you won't,
'cause I'm not putting you on the team.

910
01:13:22,564 --> 01:13:24,293
What'd you say?

911
01:13:24,566 --> 01:13:26,397
I really wanted to.

912
01:13:27,202 --> 01:13:29,966
You're not putting me on the team?
Is that what you said?

913
01:13:30,072 --> 01:13:32,836
What are you, some varsity track coach?

914
01:13:33,542 --> 01:13:38,980
They didn't buy our company 'cause
they like your lvy League charm, Jersey.

915
01:13:39,214 --> 01:13:41,011
It's me they wanted.

916
01:13:41,116 --> 01:13:44,847
You can't bench me.
It's against the laws of nature.

917
01:13:44,953 --> 01:13:48,980
You're still gonna be able
to prove that your theory is right.

918
01:13:49,091 --> 01:13:54,256
Yeah, but other scientists are gonna
evaluate my results, right? Not me.

919
01:13:54,363 --> 01:13:58,595
Everyone here reveres your science.

920
01:13:58,700 --> 01:14:03,831
This is about interpersonal issues.

921
01:14:04,573 --> 01:14:08,202
-Who put you up to this?
-The decision was mine.

922
01:14:10,412 --> 01:14:13,040
It's for the overall good of the program.

923
01:14:13,148 --> 01:14:15,878
"For the overall good of the program."

924
01:14:17,085 --> 01:14:19,553
Wow, John, you really got
the corporate lingo down good.

925
01:14:19,655 --> 01:14:22,249
What's next, "Acceptable loss?"

926
01:14:38,841 --> 01:14:39,899
No.

927
01:14:40,008 --> 01:14:41,600
Does anybody really know how to do this?

928
01:14:41,743 --> 01:14:43,301
Except for us.

929
01:14:44,513 --> 01:14:47,949
-But wait, who's going?
-It's John's turn still.

930
01:14:49,451 --> 01:14:50,713
Nice one.

931
01:14:52,287 --> 01:14:54,084
Okay. I'll get it.

932
01:15:00,629 --> 01:15:02,062
Nice one, Megs.

933
01:15:02,164 --> 01:15:05,292
Hello? Marcus, hi.

934
01:15:06,201 --> 01:15:07,327
Oh, my God.

935
01:15:07,870 --> 01:15:09,804
Man. I almost got 'em down.

936
01:15:09,938 --> 01:15:13,135
You guys sit tight, okay?
Here, John, grab him.

937
01:15:13,275 --> 01:15:17,405
If there is anything we can do,
anything at all, will you call?

938
01:15:17,946 --> 01:15:21,279
Okay.
We love you guys so much.

939
01:15:22,551 --> 01:15:24,143
Okay, bye-bye.

940
01:15:26,321 --> 01:15:27,686
Aileen.

941
01:15:30,125 --> 01:15:32,116
That was Marcus Temple.

942
01:15:33,195 --> 01:15:34,526
Lauren...

943
01:15:35,831 --> 01:15:37,093
She...

944
01:15:40,502 --> 01:15:43,232
He said she went in her sleep,
that it was peaceful.

945
01:15:43,338 --> 01:15:44,930
How old is she?

946
01:15:46,308 --> 01:15:48,208
How old was Lauren?

947
01:15:53,482 --> 01:15:55,643
Lauren was nine years old.

948
01:16:03,258 --> 01:16:04,782
Come here.

949
01:16:15,070 --> 01:16:18,904
That way, we can be certain
that we're developing the correct one.

950
01:16:19,174 --> 01:16:25,306
Forget certainty, and let's try and figure out
which enzyme has the better odds.

951
01:16:25,514 --> 01:16:28,142
If we develop only one enzyme,

952
01:16:29,618 --> 01:16:31,415
what would happen
if we guessed the wrong one?

953
01:16:31,520 --> 01:16:36,514
Mr. Crowley, I've asked Kent
to set up a testing protocol

954
01:16:36,625 --> 01:16:38,820
to help us guess right.

955
01:16:39,561 --> 01:16:42,428
We'll do an exhaustive range of tests.

956
01:16:42,531 --> 01:16:46,262
I'm calling it
"The Mother of All Experiments."

957
01:16:48,236 --> 01:16:52,730
The four enzymes will be color-coded,
yellow, blue, green and magenta,

958
01:16:52,874 --> 01:16:54,933
and known only by those color codes

959
01:16:55,077 --> 01:16:58,274
so no researcher will know
which one he's testing.

960
01:16:58,413 --> 01:17:02,713
Only after we pick a winner,
the secret identity will be revealed.

961
01:17:09,558 --> 01:17:11,219
Come on, Megan!

962
01:17:22,938 --> 01:17:24,030
But I want to!

963
01:17:29,578 --> 01:17:32,138
-Just roll your wrist.
-I can't.

964
01:17:36,618 --> 01:17:38,279
It's okay. It's all right. Let's try another one.

965
01:17:38,420 --> 01:17:40,911
Okay. Let's try again. Ready?

966
01:17:43,158 --> 01:17:44,557
Ready?

967
01:17:44,660 --> 01:17:46,821
One, two, three, go!

968
01:17:49,164 --> 01:17:51,564
-Big winner!
-Yay!

969
01:17:52,768 --> 01:17:56,101
Here you go, look at that. You got a penguin.

970
01:18:05,814 --> 01:18:07,782
Hey, Bob. Bob.

971
01:18:09,885 --> 01:18:11,477
How you doin'?

972
01:18:17,125 --> 01:18:19,184
I brought you some ribs.

973
01:18:19,995 --> 01:18:23,362
Not as good as the ones
from The Corner Saloon,

974
01:18:23,465 --> 01:18:25,490
but if you're hungry...

975
01:18:36,144 --> 01:18:37,839
What do you want?

976
01:18:40,816 --> 01:18:42,443
The results.

977
01:18:44,019 --> 01:18:45,884
"Mother of All Experiments."

978
01:18:46,021 --> 01:18:47,283
Well,

979
01:18:49,524 --> 01:18:51,617
which enzyme did they choose?

980
01:18:51,727 --> 01:18:55,288
The leadership team
spent the whole afternoon arguing.

981
01:18:55,397 --> 01:18:58,833
Two enzymes, coded yellow and green,
are ahead of the others,

982
01:18:58,934 --> 01:19:01,232
but it's too close to call.

983
01:19:01,369 --> 01:19:06,466
Tomorrow, we spend the day hashing it out
to decide which one to choose.

984
01:19:08,276 --> 01:19:11,905
Bob. I'm asking you to read this.

985
01:19:12,547 --> 01:19:15,983
I value your opinion
more than anyone else in the world.

986
01:19:16,084 --> 01:19:18,644
Well, maybe you should have valued
my opinion a little sooner,

987
01:19:18,754 --> 01:19:22,315
instead of playing hatchet man
for the bean counters.

988
01:19:23,425 --> 01:19:27,987
-Get the hell out of my lab.
-It's in your interest to know about this, Bob.

989
01:19:31,099 --> 01:19:32,498
Get out.

990
01:19:32,601 --> 01:19:35,229
-Wouldn't it benefit you...
-Get out.

991
01:19:59,661 --> 01:20:04,291
The green enzyme's the best.
Show 'em my analysis, they'll understand.

992
01:20:05,400 --> 01:20:07,095
Hey, wait up, Bob.

993
01:20:08,103 --> 01:20:09,968
Is the green enzyme yours?

994
01:20:10,105 --> 01:20:14,041
I recognize patterns in the results.
I'd know my baby a mile away.

995
01:20:14,142 --> 01:20:16,610
-So the green one is yours?
-No.

996
01:20:17,145 --> 01:20:18,737
No, it's not.

997
01:20:21,483 --> 01:20:25,647
My theory is still the best,
but it's not ready for manufacture.

998
01:20:26,922 --> 01:20:30,085
Theirs is crude and uninspired,
but it's ready.

999
01:20:31,760 --> 01:20:35,161
Bob, I don't even know the words
to say thank you.

1000
01:20:36,164 --> 01:20:37,631
Don't bother.

1001
01:20:39,801 --> 01:20:41,826
I didn't do it for you.

1002
01:21:28,683 --> 01:21:30,048
Yes, it is!

1003
01:21:32,854 --> 01:21:34,822
-Oh, my gosh. Do you see the kite up there?
-Yeah.

1004
01:21:34,923 --> 01:21:36,049
That's so cool!

1005
01:21:36,191 --> 01:21:37,852
Annie, careful!

1006
01:21:38,493 --> 01:21:40,461
-Building a bastion.
-Right there. Yeah.

1007
01:21:45,600 --> 01:21:46,726
-Three!
-Okay!

1008
01:21:46,835 --> 01:21:47,927
Dad, like... Ready?

1009
01:21:48,036 --> 01:21:51,472
-Dad, you promised no more phone calls.
-I know. I know I did, but...

1010
01:21:51,573 --> 01:21:52,597
What's in there?

1011
01:21:52,707 --> 01:21:55,005
We can take turns burying the phone
when I get back.

1012
01:21:55,110 --> 01:21:56,668
Okay! I'll start digging a hole.

1013
01:21:56,778 --> 01:21:59,406
-You hold that for a sec.
-John Crowley.

1014
01:21:59,915 --> 01:22:01,712
John, it's Kent Weber.

1015
01:22:01,850 --> 01:22:05,013
Kent, hey. Did you get
my suggested protocol for the clinical trials?

1016
01:22:06,354 --> 01:22:07,548
Yeah.

1017
01:22:09,090 --> 01:22:11,149
You made some
pretty optimistic assumptions

1018
01:22:11,259 --> 01:22:14,057
about where our enzyme supply will be.

1019
01:22:14,596 --> 01:22:15,893
I see.

1020
01:22:16,765 --> 01:22:21,293
Well, what do you think
that a more realistic...

1021
01:22:21,403 --> 01:22:27,171
John, I'll give it to you straight.
The clinical trial will be for infants only.

1022
01:22:28,476 --> 01:22:30,876
Infants need so much less enzyme,

1023
01:22:30,979 --> 01:22:33,777
and, as you know,
our initial supply will be so limited.

1024
01:22:34,249 --> 01:22:37,980
And the drug has much higher odds
of being effective

1025
01:22:38,086 --> 01:22:40,646
with infants than with older children.

1026
01:22:40,755 --> 01:22:44,191
We have to consult Erich on this.
We have to consult Erich.

1027
01:22:44,759 --> 01:22:47,626
I already did. He confirmed the decision.
Infants only.

1028
01:22:48,129 --> 01:22:51,223
I understand your personal reasons for...

1029
01:22:54,002 --> 01:22:59,235
These decisions have to be
made objectively, rationally.

1030
01:23:00,442 --> 01:23:02,569
I'm sorry. I...

1031
01:23:04,245 --> 01:23:05,269
I really am.

1032
01:26:18,940 --> 01:26:20,464
Hold it, pal.

1033
01:26:23,978 --> 01:26:27,470
-Mr. Crowley, what are you doin' in here?
-I was just...

1034
01:26:27,582 --> 01:26:31,211
-You're not authorized.
-No... I can explain everything.

1035
01:26:31,319 --> 01:26:33,184
What's the matter, Chuck?
Is there a problem?

1036
01:26:33,288 --> 01:26:36,746
Yeah, there's a problem.
I got Mr. Crowley in here without clearance.

1037
01:26:36,858 --> 01:26:38,223
That's my fault, now.

1038
01:26:38,326 --> 01:26:43,559
I got busy in the lab, I sent Jersey boy here
to get me a couple jugs of enzyme.

1039
01:26:44,132 --> 01:26:45,429
Sorry.

1040
01:26:55,510 --> 01:26:57,068
Thanks, Chuck.

1041
01:27:03,484 --> 01:27:05,645
Thanks for saving my ass.

1042
01:27:07,055 --> 01:27:09,080
It's really big of you,

1043
01:27:09,190 --> 01:27:13,786
especially after what went down between us.

1044
01:27:15,230 --> 01:27:18,529
You mean your ruthless,
cold-hearted betrayal?

1045
01:27:21,803 --> 01:27:25,830
Yeah, well, when I thought about it
from your point of view...

1046
01:27:26,574 --> 01:27:31,671
Shit, if it was my kids dying, I wouldn't
have hesitated to crush you like a bug.

1047
01:27:46,261 --> 01:27:48,525
Do you remember when we first met,

1048
01:27:48,663 --> 01:27:53,828
and you told me that
I should stop chasing miracles

1049
01:27:53,935 --> 01:27:56,836
and should go home and enjoy my kids,

1050
01:27:58,206 --> 01:28:00,367
while they're still here?

1051
01:28:05,213 --> 01:28:07,704
-Yeah.
-I made the wrong choice.

1052
01:28:23,665 --> 01:28:27,624
-Jersey, you know what a sibling study is?
-No.

1053
01:28:27,735 --> 01:28:32,604
It's a drug trial with just two patients
with the same genetic inheritance.

1054
01:28:33,841 --> 01:28:37,607
Siblings, with the same disease.

1055
01:28:37,712 --> 01:28:39,441
Megs and Patrick.

1056
01:28:41,449 --> 01:28:44,714
Well, would Zymagen
go for something like this?

1057
01:28:45,787 --> 01:28:48,585
There's real research value in it.

1058
01:28:48,756 --> 01:28:52,021
And with just two patients,
it wouldn't take much enzyme.

1059
01:28:52,126 --> 01:28:55,095
But Webber would have to sign off on it.

1060
01:28:56,264 --> 01:28:59,756
Well, let's not tell him
till we've got our ducks in a row.

1061
01:28:59,901 --> 01:29:05,203
I could draw up a protocol and see if I can
find a hospital willing to administer it.

1062
01:29:06,074 --> 01:29:09,874
-Bob.
-Well, don't get your hopes up, kid.

1063
01:29:12,180 --> 01:29:13,943
It's a Hail Mary.

1064
01:29:46,214 --> 01:29:47,841
Ducks in a row.

1065
01:29:50,818 --> 01:29:53,184
"Stonehill, careful review, protocol,
Sibling Trial,146,

1066
01:29:53,287 --> 01:29:54,720
"are pleased to inform you Megan Crowley
and Patrick

1067
01:29:54,822 --> 01:29:56,346
"have been accepted into the trial!"

1068
01:29:56,524 --> 01:29:59,220
-I just got it.
-Quack, quack, quack.

1069
01:29:59,327 --> 01:30:00,624
Have you talked to him yet?

1070
01:30:00,728 --> 01:30:04,960
No. I did the science. You make the sale.

1071
01:30:06,868 --> 01:30:08,267
Thank you.

1072
01:30:08,736 --> 01:30:10,601
-Good luck.
-Right.

1073
01:30:17,378 --> 01:30:19,278
-Does he have about five?
-He does, yeah.

1074
01:30:19,380 --> 01:30:21,848
-Thanks.
-No problem, Mr. Crowley.

1075
01:30:23,751 --> 01:30:25,719
Hey, Kent? Knock-knock.

1076
01:30:27,922 --> 01:30:29,389
Got a minute?

1077
01:30:31,025 --> 01:30:32,287
Kent?

1078
01:30:33,594 --> 01:30:37,792
-Do you have any idea what you've done?
-Excuse me?

1079
01:30:37,899 --> 01:30:40,390
We got a call this morning
from Portland Rose Hospital,

1080
01:30:40,501 --> 01:30:42,662
about sending them enzyme for your kids?

1081
01:30:42,770 --> 01:30:45,295
Right. Yeah, I know.
That's what I'm here to talk to you about.

1082
01:30:45,406 --> 01:30:49,274
You and Stonehill set this up behind
my back. Now you come to me.

1083
01:30:49,377 --> 01:30:51,277
It's all tentative.

1084
01:30:51,379 --> 01:30:55,475
You want this company
to sponsor a drug study,

1085
01:30:55,583 --> 01:30:59,917
for two children whose father
is an executive of this company?

1086
01:31:00,021 --> 01:31:02,012
Have you never heard the term
"conflict of interest?"

1087
01:31:02,123 --> 01:31:03,283
It has nothing to do with a...

1088
01:31:03,391 --> 01:31:05,188
Do you know what the FDA would do
if they found out?

1089
01:31:05,293 --> 01:31:08,490
There is strong scientific justification
for this study.

1090
01:31:08,596 --> 01:31:10,461
There is great research value.

1091
01:31:10,565 --> 01:31:13,693
I'm a doctor, John.
I know the research value!

1092
01:31:14,569 --> 01:31:17,800
But you guys just can't go off half-cocked
without consulting us!

1093
01:31:17,905 --> 01:31:19,873
And I'm sure that if we just go
and talk to Erich, we can...

1094
01:31:19,974 --> 01:31:21,373
Erich already knows.

1095
01:31:21,476 --> 01:31:25,310
-He's furious about being blindsided.
-I didn't try to blindside anyone.

1096
01:31:25,413 --> 01:31:29,008
This is the reason
why we have a reporting structure,

1097
01:31:29,116 --> 01:31:32,950
why we have established procedure,
why there is protocol.

1098
01:31:34,755 --> 01:31:37,315
You heartless, bloodless machine.

1099
01:31:37,425 --> 01:31:40,986
You just have to fight me
every step of the way! Don't you?

1100
01:31:41,095 --> 01:31:44,963
You just hated it when I brought
the kids with Pompe to the doorstep!

1101
01:31:45,066 --> 01:31:48,968
You weren't thinking about those kids when
you put your children into that program

1102
01:31:49,070 --> 01:31:53,973
and jeopardized a decade's worth of
research investment made by this company!

1103
01:31:54,075 --> 01:31:56,703
This is not about a return on an investment!

1104
01:31:56,811 --> 01:31:58,540
It's about kids,

1105
01:31:59,447 --> 01:32:02,143
kids with names, dreams,

1106
01:32:03,818 --> 01:32:05,945
families that love them.

1107
01:32:06,587 --> 01:32:10,819
You've jeopardized your chances
of ever getting your kids treated.

1108
01:32:39,320 --> 01:32:42,585
I'm not arguing science with you!

1109
01:32:43,558 --> 01:32:46,152
On every level!
On every level, you've stood...

1110
01:33:01,976 --> 01:33:05,275
I was just drafting a letter of apology
for senior management,

1111
01:33:05,379 --> 01:33:08,314
but I guess we're past that point.

1112
01:33:10,084 --> 01:33:14,180
I just spoke to Erich,
and we are terminating your employment.

1113
01:33:15,856 --> 01:33:17,790
Okay, I'll pack up my stuff.

1114
01:33:17,892 --> 01:33:19,917
Just one thing, John.

1115
01:33:20,027 --> 01:33:24,896
I may well be
a tight-ass pencil-pushing company man,

1116
01:33:24,999 --> 01:33:27,297
but I resent being called heartless.

1117
01:33:27,401 --> 01:33:29,801
-Look...
-Just let me finish.

1118
01:33:30,771 --> 01:33:33,103
The reason we're terminating
your employment,

1119
01:33:33,207 --> 01:33:36,176
is to eliminate the conflict of interest.

1120
01:33:36,877 --> 01:33:41,280
This strategy was brought to my attention
by our colleague, Dr. Stonehill,

1121
01:33:41,382 --> 01:33:43,475
in rather crude terms.

1122
01:33:45,119 --> 01:33:48,247
This will allow the sibling trial to proceed

1123
01:33:49,056 --> 01:33:51,650
for its purely scientific value.

1124
01:33:55,963 --> 01:33:59,228
Have your desk cleared out
by the end of the day.

1125
01:34:00,201 --> 01:34:02,362
Kent, what's with the...

1126
01:34:05,439 --> 01:34:10,001
I wanted to make sure you didn't
punch me out before I could tell you.

1127
01:34:11,278 --> 01:34:12,540
Well,

1128
01:34:15,049 --> 01:34:18,382
-thank you very much for firing me.
-My pleasure.

1129
01:34:18,919 --> 01:34:21,217
-I never liked you.
-Likewise.

1130
01:34:25,760 --> 01:34:27,057
Hey, you guys,
bring anything you want extra...

1131
01:34:27,161 --> 01:34:28,185
-Mom! Mom!
-What?

1132
01:34:28,295 --> 01:34:30,058
-Can I bring the bow and arrow?
-Yes, yes.

1133
01:34:33,801 --> 01:34:35,063
Hey!

1134
01:34:40,841 --> 01:34:42,433
John, what...

1135
01:34:43,411 --> 01:34:44,571
What?

1136
01:34:45,579 --> 01:34:50,983
We have a usable enzyme
that's ready for clinical trials.

1137
01:34:53,921 --> 01:34:55,821
When? When will it be ready?

1138
01:34:55,923 --> 01:34:59,723
Megs and Patrick start their infusions
before the end of this month.

1139
01:34:59,827 --> 01:35:01,954
-Oh, my God.
-Yeah.

1140
01:35:03,297 --> 01:35:04,764
Oh, my God.

1141
01:35:06,967 --> 01:35:08,161
John.

1142
01:35:08,836 --> 01:35:10,861
Hey, John, Daddy's here.

1143
01:35:10,971 --> 01:35:13,098
-Oh, hi, guys.
-Hey, Dad.

1144
01:35:13,974 --> 01:35:15,737
Why is Mommy sad?

1145
01:35:16,811 --> 01:35:19,609
Not sad, baby, so happy.

1146
01:35:22,950 --> 01:35:24,281
So happy.

1147
01:35:24,385 --> 01:35:26,285
Why is Mommy being so weird?

1148
01:35:26,387 --> 01:35:29,049
Well, it's because
we got the special medicine

1149
01:35:29,156 --> 01:35:32,592
for you, Megs, and for you, Patrick,
and you're gonna get it really soon.

1150
01:35:32,693 --> 01:35:34,126
That's great!

1151
01:35:49,710 --> 01:35:52,178
So, who wants to push the button?

1152
01:36:05,760 --> 01:36:08,524
Megs, Patrick, you ready?

1153
01:36:27,715 --> 01:36:29,979
When will we know if it's working?

1154
01:36:30,084 --> 01:36:32,143
It'll be a while, honey.

1155
01:36:32,253 --> 01:36:33,845
It's not pink.

1156
01:37:13,427 --> 01:37:16,760
Excuse me?
Your Uncle Bobby is here.

1157
01:37:18,432 --> 01:37:19,922
I don't know.

1158
01:37:27,007 --> 01:37:29,635
-You can go back if you like.
-Okay.

1159
01:37:35,082 --> 01:37:37,141
-John.
-Uncle Bobby.

1160
01:37:38,319 --> 01:37:41,447
They wouldn't let me in unless I was family.

1161
01:37:44,191 --> 01:37:47,251
-Some things for the kids.
-Thanks.

1162
01:37:47,361 --> 01:37:48,953
Sleeping, huh?

1163
01:37:54,335 --> 01:37:56,326
Hey, thanks for coming.

1164
01:38:00,307 --> 01:38:03,401
I'm a scientist. Gotta track the experiment.

1165
01:38:12,853 --> 01:38:16,311
I wish your enzyme was the one
that passed the test.

1166
01:38:16,790 --> 01:38:22,285
But the one the kids are getting,
it's the right one, right? I mean...

1167
01:38:23,030 --> 01:38:24,930
It's gonna help them.

1168
01:38:29,403 --> 01:38:31,928
Yeah, you guys have done
everything humanly possible.

1169
01:38:32,039 --> 01:38:36,271
We just have to see what the tests show.

1170
01:38:39,013 --> 01:38:41,914
You and I have had our differences,

1171
01:38:42,016 --> 01:38:45,508
and I just want you to know something.

1172
01:38:46,553 --> 01:38:48,111
I want you to know that...

1173
01:38:48,222 --> 01:38:50,019
-Yeah.
-Don't interrupt.

1174
01:38:50,124 --> 01:38:51,352
Okay.

1175
01:38:53,027 --> 01:38:57,054
I want you to know
that I appreciate everything

1176
01:38:57,164 --> 01:38:59,064
that you've done for Megs and Patrick,

1177
01:38:59,166 --> 01:39:02,761
and I'm never gonna forget it
for the rest of my life.

1178
01:39:06,473 --> 01:39:08,441
Not gonna kiss me, is he?

1179
01:39:08,542 --> 01:39:10,442
I will restrain him.

1180
01:39:11,879 --> 01:39:13,540
Don't tempt me.

1181
01:39:16,884 --> 01:39:20,684
Daddy loves SpongeBob,
Daddy loves SpongeBob.

1182
01:39:33,367 --> 01:39:35,597
-Stop!
-Daddy loves SpongeBob.

1183
01:39:35,703 --> 01:39:37,068
Guys?

1184
01:39:38,672 --> 01:39:40,367
What's going on?

1185
01:39:41,775 --> 01:39:43,504
What's so funny?

1186
01:39:44,945 --> 01:39:47,072
What are you laughing at?

1187
01:39:49,116 --> 01:39:51,243
What are you laughing at?

1188
01:39:52,119 --> 01:39:53,416
Sugar.

1189
01:39:57,124 --> 01:39:58,921
It's a sugar high.

1190
01:40:00,027 --> 01:40:03,428
The enzyme's breaking down
the sugar in their muscles.

1191
01:40:03,530 --> 01:40:06,021
-The medicine's working?
-Yeah.

1192
01:40:07,568 --> 01:40:08,762
John.

1193
01:40:17,811 --> 01:40:19,005
Megs!

1194
01:40:19,413 --> 01:40:20,505
Hi.

1195
01:40:39,199 --> 01:40:41,827
-John, drive safe!
-Enjoy the ride!

1196
01:40:44,271 --> 01:40:45,829
Rock and roll!

1197
01:40:47,307 --> 01:40:50,367
-Bye! Have fun.
-Bye!

1198
01:41:29,049 --> 01:41:30,482
Yes!

1199
01:41:31,919 --> 01:41:34,649
Yeah! Yeah!

